Lab 4: Smoking and Low Birth Weight?

R-Kelly: Lauren Tafoya, Peter Bullard, Gregor Tzinov, Ping Li, and Sasha Maslowski

February 07, 2019

Overall Questions

  1. Does smoking have increase the rate of premature delivery?
  2. Do babies of mothers who smoke have smaller weights at each gestation age?

Conclusions

ggplot(data = babies, aes(x = bwtoz, y = gestation)) + facet_wrap(~smoke)+geom_point() + geom_smooth(se = TRUE)

Our Recommendation

Based on our analyses, we conclude that smoking during pregnancy has a profound impact on the average weight and gestation period of babies. Although this trend is not obvious in most grpahics, the difference between the smoking and non-smoking population correlations between birth weight and gestation period shows our findings best. This correlation is higher within the smoking population, which shows that babies with smoking mothers born earlier are more likely to be lighter than babies of non - smoking mothers. These findings support those of the Attorney General. ##Preliminary Question

Individual Findings

Lauren

ggplot(babies,mapping=aes(x=bwtoz ,y=gestation))+geom_point()+geom_smooth()

This plot shows a higher median weight in babies whose mothers have never smoked, vs mothers who do smoke. It is also interesting to note that there is smaller distribution in Birth Weight for Non-Smoker mothers, but more outliers. Generally, one can conclude Non-Smoking mothers have babies with higher birth rates. The general health of the mothers could be a confounding factor, and it would be interesting to note the correlation between general health and smoking vs.non smoking mothers.

Peter

I created a plot that shows the differences in correlation between gestation period and all other fields for smokers and non-smokers. The figure facilitates analysis of factors other than smoking, showing their influence on the variables we are studying. The large difference in correlation between birth weight and gestation period indicates that smoking lowers birth weight at all gestation lengths, because a high correlation means that both values grow together.

The graphs demonstrate that as the mother grows in age, smoking will increase the chance that the birth will be premature. babies <- na.omit(babies)
ggplot(data = babies) +  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = as.factor(babies$smoke), fill = as.factor(babies$med)), position = "dodge") + labs(x = "Smoke")

I started by analyzing what variables are different between women who smoke or not. From the graph, we can see, women who never smoked, generally have higher education. Women who smoked have higher counts of pre-high school education. Women who didnt smoke have higher counts of high school education, some colleges education, and college graduate.

babies <- na.omit(babies) 
ggplot(data = babies) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = as.factor(babies$smoke), fill = as.factor(babies$Premature)), position = "dodge") + labs(x = "Smoke")

From the graph, we can see the counts of mom who smoke and have premature babies are slightly higher than the babies mom who dont smoke. So the Surgeon Generals first assertion is right.

ggplot(data = babies) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = babies$gestation, y = babies$bwtoz))+
  facet_wrap(~babies$smoke, nrow = 2) + labs(x = "Gestation", y = "Birth Weight") + ggtitle("How smoke affects Birth weight and Gestation")

From the graph below, we can see that mom who dont smoke, it is denser for babies to have higher birth weight and longer gestation.
